{{subspeciesbox | status = T4 | status_system = TNC | status_ref = &nbsp;<ref>{{cite web |url=http://export.nbii.gov/xml/natureserv/html/Emberizidae/0/ELEMENT_GLOBAL_2_103742.html |title=Species Profile for White-winged Junco (''Junco hyemalis aikeni'') |publisher=[[NatureServe]] |accessdate=June 8, 2010}}</ref> | genus = Junco | species = hyemalis | species_link = Dark-eyed junco | subspecies = aikeni | authority = | synonyms = ''Junco aikeni'' }}
The '''white-winged junco''' (''Junco hyemalis aikeni'') is a [[subspecies]] of the [[dark-eyed junco]]. It is superficially similar to the [[slate-colored junco]]. It was formerly classified as a distinct species.
It is a common [[endemism|endemic]] breeder in the [[Black Hills]] area of [[South Dakota]], [[Wyoming]], [[Nebraska]], and [[Montana]], and winters south along the [[Front Range]] to northeastern [[New Mexico]].<ref>Sibley (2000): pp.500-502, CLO (2002)</ref>
''J. h. aikeni'' resembles the slate-colored junco but is larger, lighter gray (the head plumage contrasting with the dark lores), has much more white in the tail, and has a larger, longer bill that often has a bluish cast. Females are paler and washed brownish. Most fresh (fall/winter) individuals have the white wingbars that give this taxon its common name, but this feature is not always present, especially in spring and summer on females as the white tips to the wing coverts easily wear off.{{Citation needed|date=April 2008}} About one slate-colored junco in 200 has wing bars as bold as those of a fresh white-winged junco. Therefore, using wingbars alone to identify a bird as a white-winged junco outside the breeding range is ill-advised; identifications must be based on all the relevant characteristics.<ref>Sibley (2000)</ref>
