{{Software development process}}

The '''Zero one or infinity (ZOI) rule''' is a [[rule of thumb]] in [[software design]] proposed{{when|date=June 2017}} by early [[computing]] pioneer [[Willem van der Poel]].<ref>http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?WillemLouisVanDerPoel</ref> It argues that arbitrary limits on the number of instances of a particular entity{{technical statement|date=June 2017}} should not be allowed. Specifically, an entity should either be forbidden entirely, only one should be allowed, or any number of them should be allowed.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.catb.org/jargon/html/Z/Zero-One-Infinity-Rule.html | title = Zero-One-Infinity Rule | work = [[Jargon File]]}}</ref> Although various factors outside that particular [[software]] could limit this number in practice, it should not be the software itself that puts a hard limit on the number of instances of the entity.

'''''"Allow none of foo, one of foo, or any number of foo."'''
''

Examples of this rule may be found in the structure of many [[file system]]s' directories (also known as folders): 
* 0 – The topmost directory has zero [[parent directories]]; that is, there is no directory that contains the topmost directory.  
* 1 – Each subdirectory has exactly one parent directory (not including shortcuts to the directory's location; while such files may have similar icons to the icons of the destination directories, they are not directories at all).  
* [[Infinity|∞ (infinity)]] – Each directory, whether the topmost directory or any of its subdirectories, according to the file system's rules, may contain any number of files or subdirectories. Practical limits to this number are caused by other factors, such as space available on [[storage media]] and how well the computer's [[operating system]] is maintained.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}}
Note that violations of this rule of thumb do exist: for example, some file systems impose a limit of 65,536 (i.e. 2<sup>16</sup>) files to a directory.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ntfs.com/ntfs_vs_fat.htm| title = NTFS vs. FAT vs exFAT | work = NTFS.com | accessdate = 2015-03-09}}</ref>

